nodes.bodyText:
My two cents: don't pass a RuntimeException or even Exception.
I have seen larger projects where in higher layers of the code have hard time to figure out what broke (just by reading the code).
Nowadays, I am big fan of just declaring a custom (so to say "business") exception for each case the implementation needs to distinguish and add the originally catched exception as cause.
Then it is easy to understand which exceptions were actually expected and the internal implementation logic is not exposed.
PS: don't declare exception as it is really hard to understand what potential issues might arise.
PPS: The last months I spent a lot of time refactoring and saw things like this:
try {
 Object a = // call to some internal object
 return a;
} catch (Exception e) {
  return null;
}

And we are still working on such things, as it takes quite some time to figure out why it is working at all (and if the catch is actually needed etc.). And many cases the exception originates from somewhere in some library and it was passed to some higher layer and then somebody added a try-catch there.
Not too much fun...

